0009|- [HelpText]
0010|*Touch mode is entered by pressing the key TOUCH. Exit takes place by ENTER.
0012|*In touch mode various computations are carried out by moving the cursor
0013|*to touch any number in the edit field and the number is activated by
0014|*pressing any of the keys +,-,* or / which correspond to standard
0015|*arithmetical operations. Several numbers can be activated in this way
0016|*and the resulting numerical expression will appear at each stage on the
0017|*bottom line of the screen.
0018|*To print the current result in the edit field, the cursor is moved to
0019|*indicate the desired position and the key = is pressed.
0021|*In touch mode more numbers and text (in lower case) can be typed in
0022|*the edit field.
0023|*Capital letters should be avoided, since a few of them have a special
0024|*function in touch mode (as seen on the next page):
0026|*Control keys in touch mode:
0027|*HELP gives information while staying in touch mode.
0028|*S evaluates the current expression without printing.
0029|*C is used to enter constants (needed in touch chains).
0030|*F enters a format (like 123.1234) for the results printed by =
0031|a@ enters a function (sqrt,log,exp,sin,cos,tan,arctan,abs,int).
0032|*M saves the current result to any of the memory locations 0,1,2,...,9.
0033|*K gets a value from memory.
0034|*PREFIX 0 clears the current result to 0 without printing it.
0036|*Touch mode is also a general tool for calculation with numerical
0037|*tables and for other repetitive computations in a form of touch chains.
0038|*A touch chain is defined in touch mode simply by performing the required
0039|*steps and letting the system to store them. In repetitive calculations
0040|*only one typical iteration is performed as a model and the system
0041|*can repeat it as many times there are numbers to touch.
0042|*To define a touch chain in touch mode, the key DISK is pressed.
0043|*Then the steps needed for the chain or for one typical iteration
0044|*are performed. To terminate the definition either EXIT is pressed
0045|*(and the chain can be reactivated by ESC) or
0046|*ESC is pressed which immediately leads to automatic repetitive
0047|*excution of the touch chain. A repetetive chain can also later be
0048|*activated by ESC.
0049|*Execution of a touch chain is automatically stopped when an edit line
0050|*with `E' in the control column is encountered. This enables computation
0051|*of tables with a fixed number of lines.
0053|*In touch chains the following keys are often useful:
0054|*R (under definition) causes the steps of the chain already entered
0055|*  to be repeated as long there are numbers to touch.
0056|*P saves the current position of the cursor and later when P is pressed
0057|*  again the cursor returns to the position saved. Thereafter a new
0058|*  position may be indicated by P.
0059|*T saves the current touch chain on disk.
0060|*L loads a touch chain saved on disk by T.
0062|*After returning to editorial mode by ENTER, a touch chain saved by T
0063|*can be loaded into the edit field by a TCHLOAD <file_name> command.
S   |                                                <         >
0064|*A chain loaded in the edit field can be saved (after it has been edited)
0065|*into a file by TCHSAVE <file_name> command.
