0068|- [New]
0069|*Collecting data in a text file in touch mode
0070|- [/New]
0072|*Numbers, words, characters and parts of edit lines can be collected
0073|*in a selected text file as consecutive lines. If the text file already
0074|*exists, new items are appended to it.
0075|*This procedure starts in touch mode by touching the (path)name of the
0076|*text file by `D'. If a space is touched by `D', file TOUCH.TXT on the
0077|*the current Survo data path is selected.
0078|*Thereafter items are selected as follows:
0079|*W saves the current word (or number) touched by the cursor,
0080|*B saves the current character,
0081|*E saves the current line to the right from the cursor.
0082|*A saves the current line to the left  from the cursor.
0084|*To stop data collecting, press `D' again or exit the touch mode by
0085|*ENTER.
0087|*The text file thus created can be processed by other means of Survo.
0088|*For example, it is loaded into the edit field by the LOADP command.
0091|- [New]
0092|*Defining a `worm' in touch mode and moving it.
0093|- [/New]
0095|*Any sequence of neighbouring characters in the edit field can be
0096|*moved like a worm across the text and copied in another place.
0097|*To define a worm, move the cursor to touch the first character
0098|*and press the WORDS (alt-F2) key. Move the cursor to touch all
0099|*other characters belonging to the worm and press WORDS again.
0100|*The worm thus defined (and highlighted) is now moved by the arrow
0101|*keys. Any time, when pressing `=' the current status of the worm
0102|*will be written in the edit field. Exit the worm mode by the WORDS key.
0103|*During the move the worm does not overwrite any text in the edit field
0104|*although it may temporarily hide it. The worm can even override itself.
0105|*Also shadow characters are moved and copied.
0107|*In worm mode, `C' clears the screen, `D' performs the display off/on
0108|*function, and `S' shows the worm with proper shadow characters when
0109|*it is moved. These options are useful in attaining visual effects
0110|*when using the worm mode in sucros.
0113|- [New]
0114|*Collecting lines
0115|- [/New]
0117|*This corresponds to the `Collecting data' procedure described above
0118|*but is simpler when copying edit lines in a new order is concerned.
0119|*Thus when staying in touch mode a set of edit lines (actually
0120|*parts of them to the right from the cursor) are selected simply
0121|*by moving the cursor by arrow keys and pressing `V'. All lines
0122|*selected by `V' are saved with their shadow lines in a temporary
0123|*file (TCHLINES.TXT).
0124|*While still staying in touch mode the selected lines are printed
0125|*to a new place (indicated by the cursor) simply by pressing `='.
0126|*The lines are displayed in the order they have been selected thus
0127|*providing `sorting' lines of tables by hand, etc.
0129|*After exit from touch mode the contents of TCHLINES.TXT is still
0130|*available. Hence when entering touch mode later, one may print
0131|*its contents by touching an empty line by `V', moving the cursor
0132|*and pressing `='.
0135|- [New]
0136|*Collecting words
0137|- [/New]
0139|*Words appearing in the current edit field can be collected in any
0140|*order by pressing '+' (like adding numbers). The sequence
0141|*of words collected appears on the bottom line in the form
0142|*word1+word2+word3+...
0143|*and this sequence is then displayed in the place selected by the user
0144|*by pressing '=' in the form
0145|*word1 word2 word3 ...
0146|*The first word must begin by a letter; otherwise the entire sequence
0147|*is interpreted as a sum of numbers.
